description.narrative:
Key results under the reporting period are as follows:
- Training in strategic analysis has been delivered for 24 police officers;
- Training in OIAT (Operational Intelligence Analysis) has been delivered to 23 police officers;
- Risk analysis course has been delivered to 36 police officers;
- Training in informant handling has been delivered to 12 police officers and 3 trainers;
- 16 operational analysts have been trained (out of these, 10 were women);
- 33 managers from Regional Police Directorates have been trained in working with ILP methodology;
- Training workshops for 80 ILP coordinators have been held to improve their capacities to perform their tasks of maintaining regular coordination with Strategic Leading Groups and Operative Leading Groups;
- 500 ILP business notebooks have been printed and distributed;
- A study visit to Sweden for 8 ILP coordinators + one representative of the Uniform Police Directorate and Sector for International Cooperation, EU Affairs and Planning each has been organized with the main goal to exchange experiences;
- A workshop has been held for 20 participants, in the form of practical exchange of experiences between the Swedish and the Serbian Police, with a particular focus on Criminal Police Directorate, Service for Combatting Organized Crime, Service for Combatting Terrorism, Department for Combatting Corruption and Service for Criminal Analysis;
- A study visit to Sweden has been organized for 6 police officers who work in the field of informant handling and controlling informant handlers;
- Meetings and experience exchange between the MoI and Swedish analysts and managers on SALW issues have been organized on both strategic and operative level, resulting in agreements and ideas regarding future cooperation;
- A study visit to Spain has been organized for 10 MoI representatives with the purpose of experience exchange aiming at developing the IT functionality of the ILP and CIS (Criminal Intelligence System);
- An IT subgroup has been established to work on designing the required IT system for ILP and defining functional requirements for the integrated database;
- An inter-agency workshop has been organized to work on the analysis of the legal framework for the National Criminal Intelligence System (NCIS). The workshop has also produced a draft inter-agency Agreement on cooperation regarding the establishment of the NCIS, which was signed on 16 September 2019;
- Training on rules and procedures of the European Commission for management of EU assistance has been held for 12 participants from the MoI's Project Management Department;
- MoI experts have participated in three ENFSI (European Network of Forensic Science Institutes) Working Groups' meetings to exchange experiences and continue upgrading the Standard Operational Procedures (SOP); 
- 36 National Forensic Center (NFC) experts have been trained in new standard ISO/IEC 17025:2017 in Quality Management System;
- 32 NFC experts have been trained as internal controllers;
- A study visit to Sweden has been organized for 3 MoI representatives (two DNA experts and one expert in forensic medicine) to introduce them to the Swedish sex crime kit;
- The complete content of the Serbian sex crime kit has been developed (user instructions included) and 350 kits have been made available;
- 6 multi-stakeholder seminar have been organized with representatives from 24 regional police directorates (forensic units and investigators), as well as prosecutors from 64 offices in these regions. During these seminars, 102 medical staff from all hospitals in these regions have been trained to use the SOP;
- Forensic consumables for seminars have been purchased and delivered to regional police directorates' forensic units;
- 18 Serbian experts from the NFC have been trained in administering the advanced protocol in interviewing child victims;
- 74 prosecutors from 64 prosecutor offices and 166 police officers have been trained on psychological needs of the victims; 
- 5 Serbian police officers have been trained in forensic intelligence system;
- A total of 56 police officers have participated in trainings on systematic integration of gender equality in police work;
- The curriculum and handbook for training-of-trainers program on gender equaility and protection against discrimination have been developed;
- 6 pilot projects have been implemented in 6 regional police directorates to incorporate the "Guidelines for implementation of measures to achieve gender equality through human resource management” in daily work. 6 trained women police officers have been assigned to work as forensic crime technicians by the new Act on Systematization;
- The Founding Assemly of the Women Police Officers Network (WPON) has been held;
- 40 persons from the WPON have received training in building the network communication capacities;
- Five promotional activities have been organized to present the goals of the WPON 25 regional police directorates and promotional material has been distributed;
- 10 police directorate managers have participated in the Gender Coaching Program (GCP). With support from the coaches, the analysis of the current state of play regarding gender equality has been performed for each relevant organizational unit;
- Individual action plans of the managers who took part in the previous cycle of the GCP have been followed up with several important anayses: the analysis of the current situation regarding the position of women in relevant organizational units, assessment of the gender disbalance in the award and training system and preparation of the promotion plan for the integration of gender equality in a regional police directorate.
